---
import Layout from "../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "../../../components/Header.astro";
import imageNew3 from "../images/new-3.png";
import imageNew4 from "../images/new-4.png";
import imageNew5 from "../images/new-5.png";
const { useLayout } = Astro.props;
---

<Layout
 title="Week 11"
 dir="w11/"
 displayLayout={useLayout}
 chapterSubSections={[]}
>
 <Header id="D">
  <h1>Dynamic Arrays</h1>
 </Header><div>
  <p class="firstLine">
   You can also create arrays on the heap; these are called <mark>
    dynamic arrays</mark
   >. Follow the type name with the desired number of elements enclosed in
   square brackets:
  </p>
  <img
   src={imageNew3}
   class="right width-30"
   style="margin-top:-.5em;"
   alt="A new dynamic array."
  />
  <pre
   class="language-cpp"
   style="width:65%;"><code>double *da = new double[3];</code></pre>
  <p>
   Here, <tt>da</tt> points to <mark>the first <tt>double</tt></mark>
   in a block of memory large enough to hold three <tt>double</tt>s. Treat <tt
    >da</tt
   > as an array whose storage <strong>lives in the heap</strong> rather than on
   the stack. Remember to
   <mark>save the size of the array</mark>, though, since, you cannot use the
   "sizeof trick" on a dynamic array.
  </p>
  <p>
   Before C++ 11, elements of a dynamic array were
   <strong>uninitialized</strong>. With the new standard, you can value
   initialize (that is, <strong>set to zero for primitive types</strong>),
   <mark>all the elements</mark> on the heap by using a set of empty parentheses
   after the square brackets.
  </p>
  <img
   src={imageNew4}
   class="right width-30"
   style="margin-top:-.5em;"
   alt="A new dynamic array zero initialized."
  />
  <pre
   class="language-cpp"
   style="width:65%;"><code>double *da = new double[3]();</code></pre>
  <p>
   Now, each element pointed to by the <tt>da</tt>
   pointer is guaranteed to hold <tt>0.0</tt>.
  </p>
  <p>
   You can also use <mark>list-style uniform initialization</mark> to partly initialize
   a dynamic array:
  </p>
  <img
   src={imageNew5}
   class="right width-30"
   style="margin-top:-.5em;"
   alt="A new dynamic array initialized."
  />
  <pre
   class="language-cpp"
   style="width:65%;"><code>double *da = new double[3]&lbrace;1, 2&rbrace;;</code></pre>
 </div>
</Layout>
